DARREN DAHL: Radiohead was at a crossroads in 2007.

3
00:00:09,570 --> 00:00:10,690
Why?

4
00:00:10,690 --> 00:00:13,290
Well, they had a regular label that they had been using

5
00:00:13,290 --> 00:00:15,910
for their previous six albums, EMI.

6
00:00:15,910 --> 00:00:19,520
But they decided to part ways with them in 2003.

7
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:23,670
This band, a very popular band out of the UK,

8
00:00:23,670 --> 00:00:27,210
had a new album that they wanted to launch in 2007,

9
00:00:27,210 --> 00:00:28,920
and this was called In Rainbows.

10
00:00:28,920 --> 00:00:31,670
But they didn't quite know what they were going to do.

11
00:00:31,670 --> 00:00:38,670
Should they go with a regular label, a distributor and make $1.50 an album?

12
00:00:38,670 --> 00:00:41,850
That had been the norm, and that's what they were used to.

13
00:00:41,850 --> 00:00:43,710
But they thought, here's the opportunity.

14
00:00:43,710 --> 00:00:45,360
We aren't signed with anyone.

15
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:49,840
Let's experiment with pricing with distribution and see what we can do.

16
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:51,730
And that's what I want to talk about today.

17
00:00:51,730 --> 00:00:55,430
I'm going to set Paul up a little bit with this story about Radiohead.

18
00:00:55,430 --> 00:00:58,980
Because you see, pricing is an interesting strategic lever

19
00:00:58,980 --> 00:00:59,945
in marketing.

20
00:00:59,945 --> 00:01:04,209
And in this context, Radiohead really took an interesting gamble.

21
00:01:04,209 --> 00:01:06,100
They tried something new.

22
00:01:06,100 --> 00:01:10,880
You see, at this time, you could download a whole album for $9.99

23
00:01:10,880 --> 00:01:13,330
or an individual song for $0.99.

24
00:01:13,330 --> 00:01:16,950
And Radiohead thought, maybe there's something different here, something

25
00:01:16,950 --> 00:01:18,490
we can experiment with.

26
00:01:18,490 --> 00:01:22,190
And so they launched this album on their website.

27
00:01:22,190 --> 00:01:26,990
And they asked their fan base, and potential customers actually,

28
00:01:26,990 --> 00:01:30,810
if you want to buy the album, and you had to buy the whole album,

29
00:01:30,810 --> 00:01:34,490
you can buy it, and you can pay whatever you want.

30
00:01:34,490 --> 00:01:36,550
This is one of the best examples of a pricing

31
00:01:36,550 --> 00:01:40,080
strategy known as name your own price.

32
00:01:40,080 --> 00:01:43,190
The question is, was it successful?

33
00:01:43,190 --> 00:01:45,180
Because Radiohead took a real gamble.

34
00:01:45,180 --> 00:01:47,440
They had a very loyal fan base.

35
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:51,260
And the notion of name your own price obviously caught a lot of attention.

36
00:01:51,260 --> 00:01:53,880
It was great PR.

37
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:55,540
It was counter culture as well.

38
00:01:55,540 --> 00:01:58,500
And that's something that Radiohead embraces as a brand.

39
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:03,550
They're not your regular pop type band in any sense of the word.

40
00:02:03,550 --> 00:02:05,950
And so obviously, this appealed to their fan base

41
00:02:05,950 --> 00:02:10,130
and frankly attracted more people to the Radiohead banner.

42
00:02:10,130 --> 00:02:11,670
So what happened?

43
00:02:11,670 --> 00:02:16,340
Well, two out of five of the people that downloaded the album,

44
00:02:16,340 --> 00:02:18,090
paid something for it.

45
00:02:18,090 --> 00:02:21,690
And the average price paid was $6.

46
00:02:21,690 --> 00:02:25,190
